# Qwen-Code (Apex) — Cursor Spoke Rules

## Role
You are working on the TypeScript universal CLI agent harness (codename Apex). This is a fork of QwenLM/qwen-code (itself a fork of Google Gemini CLI) with multi-provider cross-wire support.

## Why This Matters
Apex is one of two universal harnesses in a cross-wire CLI agent project. Traditional agents are monolithic — one wire, one model. Apex speaks ALL THREE wire protocols (generateContent native, /responses shipped, /messages shipped) through a pluggable ContentGenerator architecture with four implementations. It can drive Claude, GPT, Gemini, Qwen, and DeepSeek from the same TS codebase.

Your work here — whether extending converters, closing null-space gaps, or adding harness features — directly expands what models this harness can drive and how faithfully.

**Two tiers — know which branch you're on**:
- `dev` = PUBLIC tier (netbrah GitHub). The engine. All cross-wire implementations, converters, and unique features live here. This is open-source and upstreamable.
- `feat/apex-embed-assets` = PROPRIETARY tier (NetApp APEX). A thin chassis on top of dev: ~11 commits for APEX branding, ONTAP skills, MCP configs, proxy integration, SEA binary. Maximize dev, minimize this layer.

## Orientation
1. Check current branch: `git branch --show-current`
2. If on `dev`: public-facing development. Features here can be upstreamed.
3. If on `feat/apex-embed-assets`: NetApp proprietary layer (~11 commits on top of dev). Contains APEX branding, custom skills, MCP configs, SEA binary build, npm distribution.
4. If on a `feat/` or `fix/` branch: you are working on a specific feature/fix. Commit there.
5. Read `AGENTS.md` for project context.

## Architecture
- **Language**: TypeScript (monorepo: `packages/cli/`, `packages/core/`)
- **Internal format**: Google `@google/genai` Content[] types — the lingua franca
- **ContentGenerator pattern**: Pluggable interface with 4 implementations:
  - `GeminiContentGenerator` — native generateContent
  - `OpenAIContentGenerator` — /chat/completions + /responses
  - `AnthropicContentGenerator` — /messages
  - `QwenContentGenerator` — DashScope/Qwen specific
- **Upstreams**: QwenLM/qwen-code (`upstream`), google-gemini/gemini-cli (`gemini`)

## Key Files
- `packages/core/src/core/anthropicContentGenerator/converter.ts` — Gemini <-> Anthropic (581 lines)
- `packages/core/src/core/openaiContentGenerator/converter.ts` — Gemini <-> OpenAI (1363 lines)
- `packages/core/src/core/openaiContentGenerator/streamingToolCallParser.ts` — truncation detection (unique feature)
- `packages/core/src/core/openaiResponsesContentGenerator/` — /responses pipeline
- `packages/core/src/core/contentGenerationPipeline.ts` — request/response pipeline
- `packages/core/src/core/claudeConverter.ts` — Claude plugin/extension converter (823 lines)

## Branch Strategy
- `dev` is a clean linear stack with all public features
- `feat/apex-embed-assets` is `dev` + 11 proprietary commits on top
- Cherry-pick from dev → apex is trivial (linear stack)
- Never push feat/apex-embed-assets to public remotes

## Unique Features (not in upstream)
- Multi-provider ContentGenerator architecture (FQ-1)
- Anthropic /messages full integration (FQ-2)
- OpenAI /responses full integration (FQ-3)
- StreamingToolCallParser truncation detection (FQ-7)
- Orphaned tool call cleanup via cleanOrphanedToolCalls() (FQ-3)
- Schema compliance modes (FQ-8)
- Modality gating system (FQ-9)
- Arena mode (FQ-6)
- Claude plugin converter (FQ-5)

## Build & Test
```bash
npm run build          # Build all packages
npm run test           # Run unit tests (Vitest)
npm run lint           # ESLint
npm run preflight      # Full CI check
npm run bundle         # Bundle for distribution
```

